Too little, too late.
Going to be closer than I expected, but not much time left (and I'm not sure there will be any updates over the weekend?)

Biden got a little bit of a last-minute bounce. He's currently at 39.3%. I'm thinking that perhaps it's because he's been recovering from COVID, so a subset of the population is a bit sympathetic and currently regards him in a more favorable light than they normally do.

The climate agreement, thanks to the Damascene conversion of Senator Joe Manchin, may move some progressive voters to the "approve" column. With so little time left it's a long shot, but there is little downside to moving a few beans from 35-40% to 40-45%.
Virtually certain..
Biden’s last hope of a small bump from legislation successes is all but dashed. The numbers are backed in now.
As of today 25Jul22, Biden's approval rating on 538 is 37.7%.
Updating for time
Too close to 31 July for any survey results to move the pin given 538's approach.
Rolling down the hill... 538 has it at 37.4%.
Calling it. Not enough time for meaningful improvement in the rating unless something extraordinarily positive for Biden (and super unlikely) happens in the next few days.
Looks increasingly unlikely to cross 40% threshold.
Concentrating forecast around 35-40 as time elapses
What a Maroon
Given the worsening economical situation, don't imagine why current approval ratings of 38% would budge. I don't see any reason why would it improve given the trend
See more risk weighted to the downside from current.
Even the hardcore Dems are after poor Biden, so they can save their seats in the by-election.
Updating for time elapsed
Inflation might be a good heuristic here and considering that nothing has improved in June and probably ditto for July - so Biden might stay below 40%.

After plateauing circa 40-42% in the first 4ish months of the year, Biden's approval rating has been in steady decline in May-June. Bit of a drastic shift of my forecast into the 35-40 category, but ought to have updated earlier.

Rating finally dropped below 40%. Looking at the recent range of polls the 90% range looks to be 45% to 35% but there are very few recent polls at seems to be much over 40% with quite a few closer to 35% so I expect the approval rating to keep sliding.
Double whammy of gasoline inflation plus republican isolationism backlash.
Support is eroding slowly but surely, looks like he’ll tip below the 40% very soon, so swinging my forecast.
40.2% today. Surprised it got so low. Clearly there is a good chance of going just a bit lower by end-July.
Bad luck and bad messaging

I don't think his approval rating is rising from the present 41% value, and the people who still approve are probably unaffected by inflation. I estimate that a third of the population isn't even paying attention, so I doubt he'll go below 35% under any circumstances.
seem to be consistently in the low 40's - next couple of months with inflation, baby formula shortage will be critical in ratings for next few months

All year long, this administration's core supporters seem unwavering at 40ish. I think this will continue though further pain will be had in increasing mortgage rates, a correcting S&P index, and paying through the nose for food and gas (I ranted about $38 at McDonald's on Mother's Day for 4 breakfast meals). All in all, the tradeoff for $3 hashbrowns is more than worth it to the 40% of adults still recovering from 4 years of panic attacks.

Difficult to envision a scenario that dramatically changes Biden's numbers between now and July 31, so bumped up the 40-45 category. Somewhat downward weight in the other categories as he's been floating in the lower part of the 40-45 bracket lately.
A lot has changed since January…except for Biden’s approval rating! Increasingly hard to see how that will change in our timeframe.

News on the economy looks like it’ll be getting worse before it gets better. Inflation is really starting to erode people’s purchasing power, becoming a homeowner is getting more difficult/risky because of high price level, and there’s a lot of anxiety about everything from when the next big bad COVID variant shows up to what happens next with Ukraine/Russia to personal security given the increasing crime statistics. Oh, and half the country still thinks that the other half is crazy/at fault/responsible for the mess we’re in.
used the wisdom of the crowd approach in my Cognitive Psych course

When things go well for Biden it doesn't seem to move the polls much. But when things go badly his numbers go down. People are in a bad mood after two years of pandemic, and now high inflation. Low unemployment doesn't seem to help him. Personally I don't need or want to be entertained by my president, but it also seems that many people do. Love him or hate him, Trump was an entertainer. Biden is definitely not.
revising based on April 7 data - currently hovering at 41.7%; hasn't dipped below 40.4% since end of February
Absent some black swan event, I don't see a significant change in the current trajectory.

My rationale for this question is similar to the other questions about 538 approval rating averages. I don't think Biden can get above 50%, and I don't think he will ever get below 35%. Between the middle three buckets, then, I think there's a slim chance he ends up below 40% given that seems to kind of be the floor for the modern presidency in the last two administrations.
don't see administration leadership on core issues of economy/ inflation; immigration; foreign policy
Of course if he suspends the fuel taxes between now and then his poll numbers could soar.
Given trends 40-45 seems the most likely outcome.
Probably overdid it with the “flatness” of my initial forecast.

As I write this he’s around 42%, the 90% confidence goes below 40% and above 45%. I doubt he’ll improve, but his polls still could wiggle up a few %. Maybe his approval will stabilise but if not then there is the option for it to move down further. Still not sure if I can think his base will be small enough to shrink below 35% due to partisanship though I can imagine 33% somehow

Seems a sustained small bump is anticipated and bigger bump will only happen if the conflict with Russia widens. https://edition.cnn.com/2022/03/13/politics/biden-approval-gas-prices-ukraine/index.html https://www.npr.org/2022/03/04/1084463809/biden-approval-poll-ukraine-economy
Historic polling shows that approval ratings consistently fall throughout Presidents' first term. The biggest factors that will be in play over the coming months for Biden paint the same picture:
Current efforts not meeting with lots of support. Bounce or bust from his efforts on the Ukraine, and their consequences on the American economy
Biden's been stuck in the 40-45 band since he dropped into it at the beginning of October, nearly dropping below in February.

Polling on Presidential approval is arguably more partisan than any period of our history. Bubbles of information are more and more segregated. While, all demonstrate degrees of bias, many right-wing media outlets to include mainstream, e.g., FOX, are promoting demonstrably false narratives. Those who live in such an info-sphere will be hard pressed to ever approve of Biden regardless of what he says and does. This results in a baked in disapproval of 38-42 percent. Also baked in is a President in crisis. Pandemic, inflation, and war are challenges a President has little or no control over. But the resultant chaos of such crises also presents opportunities for demonstration of leadership. Recent successes in unifying the West against authoritarian overreach could lead to similars efforts domestically. Centrists are likely to lean towards reality-based leadership. Finally, approval is not a gauge of support. Biden supporters can also disapprove. These factors will likely keep Biden's approval rating between 40-50 percent.
Ukraine war, COVID receding, economy improving point towards a gentle improvement, but all of these incorporate downsides as well, and there is a good deal of uncertainty.
Republican disinformation machine will effectively blame Biden for all negative events.
people will get in a better mood and his rating will rise

The Ukrainian War will be used as an excuse to keep hiking gas prices and with rising gas, continuing inflation will continue to drag down Biden's popularity. The only upside is if his administration can get people convinced that high gas prices are Patriotic and support the people of Ukraine. I don't think it likely though.
Rally 'round the flag' effect?

my forecast right now is just based on a gut feeling - i believe he'll be in the 35-45 range - but i think a lot will be influenced by what continues wiht ukraine, as well as domestic impacts - there is the potential for it to fall below 35
President Biden's approval rating has jumped post delivering his annual speech, however according to FivethirtyEight, as of March 8 22, his disapproval rating hit 51.9%.

Biden's ratings are currently most strongly influence by (a) inflation/economy, (b) US response to the Russian invasion of Ukraine, (c) US withdrawal from Afghanistan and (d) sizeable contingent of US citizens who are convinced that whatever he does is wrong. Russian is resolved to gain control of Ukraine and will most likely prevail eventually. The world will continue to continue to sanction Russia at the price of worsening inflation. With midterm elections approaching, Republicans will be stepping up rhetoric on Biden's shortcomings.

I assume Russia doesn't do anything stupid...like starting a nuclear war...Joe's easy approach should win him points. A policy of gradually increasing pressure on Russia/Putin should bear fruit IF he applies the pressure slowly. We want Putin to be a frog in a pot of water placed over the burner, not realizing he's boiling until it's too late for him to act. That's hard for Americans or anyone else to see so I don't see a big swing by August. If Ukraine falls or if Putin comes to the table to make a deal, the results can move up or down.

During times of geopolitical turmoil the country traditionally rallies around the president and government. But with inflation and a number of other factors I think the approval rating will stay close to where it is currently.
Covid will ease, people will feel better about their lives. https://www.npr.org/2022/03/03/1084113686/with-covid-easing-the-white-house-has-a-plan-for-things-to-return-to-normal
Here comes the rise in gas and other products above the current FU US inflation 0f 7.5

So July is not that far away. On the other hand, Biden's approval rating seems to be one straight line down with a step change after Afghanistan. In the last week it has improved (I understand Americans think he is doing ok on Ukraine...). Looking at Trump he fell below 40% sometimes (not below 35%) but mostly stabilised at low 40's. On the basis of floor levels of support and recent stabilisation the 40-45% bin seems pretty likely with potential to drift to the 2 adjacent based on events. (I have weighted 45-50 a bit higher than 34-50 on the basis of patriotism during war).

I think there’s a pretty good likelihood of a rally around the flag effect will occur given the current Ukraine war and US-Russia tensions, at least in the short term. Of course this may fade as economic conditions change (likely greater inflationary pressures at some point that could weigh on his popularity)
Will not get better. Also 538 runs high. Other polls have him lower.

It’s hard to see popularity going outside the 40-45pc range. Opinions are entrenched. If the situation with Russia escalates popularity is more likely to go up, but I think that, say NATO goes to war with Russia, people may approve of that, but i’m not sure it would move Biden popularity that much. You can approve of something, it doesn’t make you like the person doing it more.

NPR said today Biden's approval rating was a 47% after his SOTU address, which would represent an 8 pt jump. That's a lot, seems off. His SOTU was crafted with statements that poll well and times of war tend to bring the country together, jobs report today was good, and most pandemic restrictions are being lifted across the nation, but oil/gas continue to rise, and so is inflation -- both expected to continue to rise given the war in Ukraine. The 538 polling average is showing 42%. He's set to make very difficult decisions in the next couple of weeks, hard to tell now how the Ukraine conflict will escalate but Putin is giving indications he will continue to test NATO and conduct an even more brutal campaign.

Biden's approval rating has remained within the 40-45% band since the end of September. Similar to Trump, it seems he has a floor of support somewhere around 40%. His support remained in the 50-55% range (honeymoon) until the Delta wave hit the country, then fell further during the chaotic Afghanistan withdrawal. COVID (Omicron) is retreating, but it doesn't seem to show up in the numbers. Why? I have no idea. Inflation worries? War? Ukraine has been handled well, IMHO, and should be a positive. His numbers did increase a couple of points after the SOTU address.
Such volatile times make this a particularly difficult one to guess but assuming that the conflict with Russia persists it seems unlikely a very low popularity rating will persist
Initial highly subjective forecast, extrapolating from current trends, and comparing with the trajectory of Obama’s approval numbers.

Its not in his hands, but this rests on how fed actions put breaks on inflation and the way things play our in Ukraine / Russia. Sticking with status quo until more data on either of these two fronts.
